d, United Kingdom","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1463–1502":"1463–1502","1464–1517":"1464–1517","1465–1517":"1465–1517","1486–1517":"1486–1517","1488–1587":"1488–1587","1502":"1502","1488":"1488","1587":"1587","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1464":"1464","1463":"1463","1517":"1517","Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Adderbury, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1463–1502":"1463–1502","1464–1517":"1464–1517","1465–1517":"1465–1517","1486–1517":"1486–1517","1488–1587":"1488–1587","1502":"1502","1488":"1488","1587":"1587","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1464":"1464","1463":"1463","1517":"1517","Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fox","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from a word denoting the animal (Middle English, Old English <i>fox</i>), widely used to denote a sly or cunning individual. It was also used for someone with red hair. In England this surname absorbed some early examples of surnames derived from the ancient Germanic personal names mentioned at   Faulks   and   Foulks  .","Irish: part translation of Gaelic <b>Mac an tSionnaigh</b> ‘son of the fox’ (see   Tinney  ).","Irish: also adopted for <b>Ó Catharnaigh</b>, see   Kearney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Foxe","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Fox  .","Altered form of English   Fox  ."]},{"name":"Foxx","meanings":["Variant of   Fox  ."]},{"name":"Faulks","meanings":["English: from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fauque</i>, <i>Fauques</i>, <i>Fau(l)ques</i> (oblique case <i>Fau(l)que</i>), originally an ancient Germanic byname <i>Falco</i>, meaning ‘falcon’."]},{"name":"Foxman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Charna, Isadore, Shmuel.","Jewish (American): variant of   Fox  ."]},{"name":"Fuchs","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Hans, Kurt, Gerhard, Fritz, Mathias, Matthias, Armin, Ulrich, Erwin, Helmut.","German and Jewish: from Middle High German <i>vuhs</i>, German <i>Fuchs</i> ‘fox’, a nickname for a sly or cunning person, or for someone with red hair. This surname is also found in France (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Poland, Czechia, and Slovenia, often as a translation into German of corresponding Slavic nicknames or surnames. Compare   Fox   4,   Fuks  , and   Futch  ."]},{"name":"Kearney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Seamus, Caitlin, Declan, Dermot, Donovan, Eamonn, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Catharnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Catharnach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘warlike’. Alternatively, it may be from <b>Ó Cearnaigh</b> or <b>Mac Cearnaigh</b> (from <i>cearnach</i> ‘victorious’) or from <b>Ó Ceithearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceithearnach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘foot soldier’.","History: Most present-day bearers of this name are descended from Tadhg Ó Catharnaigh, killed in battle in 1084. He was nicknamed <i>An Sionnach</i> ‘the Fox’, and for this reason the Irish surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Fox  . Denis Kearney, born in Oakmont, Ireland, in 1847, was a US labor movement leader."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Davis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the surname, in origin a patronymic from the given name   Davy .  Use as a given name is often in honour of  Jefferson Davis  (  1808–89 ), President of the Confederate States during the Civil War."],"variants":[{"name":"Davies","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the surname, in origin a patronymic from the given name   Davy .  Use as a given name is often in honour of  Jefferson Davis  (  1808–89 ), President of the Confederate States during the Civil War."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"John Davis Fox was born in 1463, in Northumbria, England. He married Elizabeth Hannah. They were the parents of at least 1 son. His occupation is listed as merchant in London, England. He died in 1502, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1463–1502":"1463–1502","1464–1517":"1464–1517","1465–1517":"1465–1517","1486–1517":"1486–1517","1488–1587":"1488–1587","1502":"1502","1488":"1488","1587":"1587","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1464":"1464","1463":"1463","1517":"1517","Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Adderbury, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1463–1502":"1463–1502","1464–1517":"1464–1517","1465–1517":"1465–1517","1486–1517":"1486–1517","1488–1587":"1488–1587","1502":"1502","1488":"1488","1587":"1587","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1464":"1464","1463":"1463","1517":"1517","Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Adderbury, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Northumbria, England":"Northumbria, England","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1463–1502":"1463–1502","1464–1517":"1464–1517","1465–1517":"1465–1517","1486–1517":"1486–1517","1488–1587":"1488–1587","1502":"1502","1488":"1488","1587":"1587","1465":"1465","1486":"1486","1464":"1464","1463":"1463","1517":"1517","Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Adderbury, Oxfords